as rine 3% 6\nReal EStatl...ccoorresnsasasnsiens \u00a31 or\nPROSPERITY SURE,\nSAYS PRESIDENT\nExpresses Confidence in Na\ntion, in Address to\nDelegates.\nPresident Roosevelt today expressed\nthe utmost confitence in the return of\nprosperity and ir: an address to a del\negation representing the National Pros\nperity Assceiation, assured his hearers\nthat the wowk mapped out for the fu\nture by the Administration contains no\nmenace {oo Husiness.\nThe prosperity committee consisted of\nE. C. Simmons, chairman; W. K. Bixby,\nvice chairiaan; J. E. Smith, Edward\nDevoy, Murray Carlton, George Meyer,\nJackson Johnson, and F. B. Wiberg, of\nConnecticut.\nIn addressing the President, Mr. Sim\nmons, head of the largest hardware es\ntablishments in the world, made a plea\nfor his support In the work of the as\nsociation in bettering trade relations\nnot only between business men, but be\ntween capital and labor. He clalined\nthat business has suffered much froin\ndemagogic agitation by professional\nagitators,\u201d and that it would be one of\nthe chief aims of the organization to\nchange all this and to deprecatle the\nunworihy spirit which arrays class\nagainst class.\nIn reply, the President said:\n\u201cI am in hearty sympathy with the\nsvowed object of the Nationa! Prosperi\ntv Association. It is excellent. We have\ngone far in uprooting abuses whict\nthreaten our national life, Taken as\nwhole, the standard of honesty in ou\nbusiness life has been high, and toda)\nthe standard is, IT believe, beyond wha\nit hzs ever been, and this largely be\ncause we nave made determired war ol\n{he abuses that lowered it. As you havi\nsaid, the depression and stagnation [ron\nwhich our country is now happily begin\nning to recover, were not caused by re\nform legislation, but by the revelation\nof shocking conditions in certain of ou\ncorporations, by reckless operations i\nkigh finance, by calamity, and by cer\ntain striking, though, I believe, excep\ntional, instances of business and civi\naishonesty.\n\u201cyf course, all good men Must agre\npo vou 'n your commendation of un\nwise agitation. The apathetic accep\ntance of abuses in our governmenta\nand business administrations is no mor\ndangerous than the demagogic appeal\nof professional agitators to class ha\n\u2018reds. Our national conscience, I firm\n'yv believe, has been awakened.\u201d\nPHILIP GERRY DEAD\nAT MARYLAND HOME\nProminent in Washington News\npaper Circles for the Last\nThree Years.\nPhilip P. Gerry, Sunday editor of the\nEvening Stas, did at his home in Mary\nland at 11 o'clock this morning. No ar\nrangements have been made for the fu\nneral, because Mr. Gerry's five brothers\nand sisters have not been heard from.\nMr. Gerry was born in Catonsville,\nahotit forty-three vears ago. He attend\ned the publt\u00e9 schoel, and afterward\nwent to Johns Hopkins, where he com\npleted the academic course. After\ngraduating he became professor of Eng\nlish at the Central High School of\nwashington, and later went 10 the Mec\nKinley building.\nThree vears ago he resigned his posi\ntion at the school te join the staff\nof the Siar. After a year's service he\nbecame assistant Sunday editor. For the\nlast vear, however, he served as Sun\nday editor,\nIn 19% Mr. Gerry married Miss Mar\nguerite Spalding in Washington. His\nwidow and two children, Harvey and\nMargory, survive him.\nMr. Gerry was ill but two weeks with\ntyphoid fever. Until within one hour\nof nis death doctors and relatives be\nlieved he weunld recover.\nMr. Gerrv has many friends in the\nnewspaper business and his death came\nas 3 great shocl to those who knew his\nsterling worth, genial disposition and\nforceful character and ability.\nJ. RALPH HEADS\nENGRAVING BUREAU\n\nCortelyou Appoints Assistant\nDirector to Thomas J.\nSullivan's Place.\nSecretary Cortelyou today zpoocinted\nJoseph B. Ralph director of the Bureau\nof Ergraving and Printing, to succeed\nthe late Thomas J. Sullilvan, as fore\ncust ii. The Times Saturday.\nMr. Ralph was the assistant director\nunder Director Sullivan, and has been\nconnected with the hurexu for twalve\nyears, lLiolding at one time the position\nof custodian of dies, rolls, znd pilates.\nHe is a native of Allegheny City, Pa.\n\u2018and a legal resident of Joliet, lil, where\nhe was employed as an expert mechanie\nin the steel works before coming to\nWashington.\nIie algo served as vice president of the\nAmalgamated Assoclation of Iron and\nSteel Workers, taking a prominent and\n\u2018active interest in the affairs of organ\nized labor. He has been an active and\nconsistent Republican and had the sup\nport of Speaker Cannon and the Re\npublican members of the Illinois dele:\ngation in Congress.\nPopular With Employes.\nMr, Raiph has taken an active part\nin the movement to secure a hew build\ning for the Bureau of Engraving and\nPrinting, His appointment hag been\nwell received by the employes of the\nbureau, many expressions of good will\nand pleasure at his promotion already\nhaving been tendered the new director.\nIt ig understood that the position of\nassistant director will go to James M.\nFisher, appointment and correspondence\ncificer and confidential secretary to the\ndirector.\nCONVENTION HALL\n10 GO AT AUCTION\nThe largest piece of really offered at\nauction in many years has been adver\ntised for public sale by Thomas J. Owen\nSon for next Friday afternoon at 4\no'clock. The old Northern Liberty Mar\nket ang Convention Hall, the former\nerected in 1874 and (he latter in 1891, at\nthe corner of K, L, and Fifth streeis\nnorthwest, are to be sold to satisfy the\nholders ofe $125.00 of bonds, which the\ncompany owning the property issued,\nand upon which the interest has been\nallowed to lapse.\nThe Trust Company of North Amer\nfica, which holds the bonds and a mort\ngage on the property, is now proceeding\nto foreclose.\nThe property is owned by a stock\ncompany, a majority of the shares of\nwhich, it is understood, are held by\nStilson Hutching.\nThe property fronts 184 feet both on\nK ang 1. streets, and nearly 324 feet\non Fifth street. It hos been used for\nthirty-four vears as a market place.\nThomas J. Owen, the auctioneer, who\nwill copduct the sale, is an expert\nrealty eppraiser. He gave it as his\nopinion today that the property was\nworth at least $250,000.\nThe National Savings and Trust Com\npany has sold through Stone Fairfax\nthe three-story dwelling, 215\u00b0 G sireet\nnerthwest, The purchaser will improve\nthe house and occupy fit as his resi\ndence.\n5 5 ISSUE OF STOCK\nOpen for Subscription.\n3\nETRE\nShares, $2.50 Per Month.\n\nEQUITABLE\nCo-operative Building\nAssociation\nOffice Equitable Building, 1003 F St. N.W.\n\nJNO. JOY EDSON, President.\nFRANK P. REESIDE, Secretary.\nCall or Write for Pamphlet.\nSECURITY\n\n4\nMay be obtained and anxiety avoided at small\nexpense by placing\u2019 your valuable papers, jew\nys sas bibl L  clry, and securities in a safe deposit box.\nBoxes are rented by the Company for the\nyear at $3.00 and upward.\nTHE\nWASHINGTON LOAN AND\nTRUST COMPANY.\nE:\n\nCapital and Surpius, $1,700,00C\nJOHN JOY EDSON, President.\nSOR. STH AND STS.\nFinancial.\nPAY TWD FARES\nNEW CAR PLAN\n\ni i\nSuburbanites Want to Keep\nCity Passengers Off\nTheir Trolleys.\nA movement is on foot to secure an\namendment to the Union Station track\nage bill which will authorize the elec\ntric railroad companies, operating cars\nbevond the Distriet of Columbia, to\ndesignate certain cars upon which two\nfares must be paid by all persons take\ning them-the first fare for passage in\nthe District and the second for the first\nfare after the car leaves the District\nline.\nThe object of this measure is to en\nable the railroads to overcome the pres\nent congested condition of suburban\ntravel, il being irapossible, under ex\nisting conditicns, to prevent passengers\nresiding in the District trom crowding\nthe cars upon which passengers living\nbeyond the District must necessarily\ntravel.\nFor example, it is claimed that the\nRockville cars of the Rockville and\nGeorgetown line are, during certain\nbusy hours, much crowded, while ine\nWest Chevy Chase cars, going out with\nin a few minutes of \u2018he same time, have\nmany empty seats. It is claimed that\nif such an amendment were taken ad\nvantage of by that railroad, it would\nresult in providing seats for the Dis\ntrict people on their own cars, and re\nlleving the congesiion on the kville\nCars,\nH. T. Newcomb, presiden* of the\nBetheseda Citizens\u2019 Association, ha:\ntaken tine matter up on behalf of the\nassociation, and pes that the propo\nsition will meet with no objection fron\nthe railroad companies, the people, oO\nthe District Commissioners.\nCITY BANK SALE\nMAY GO THROUGH\nit is reported in financial circies that\nthe interests that have been trying for\na month to secure a controlling interest\nir the National City Pank, have about\nconcluded negotiations.\nOn the Stock Exchange, the fArs: pid\nthis morning for National City Bank\nstock showed something doing, and fit\nquickly was raised to $15 a share or\n$0 over Saturday's price.\nCashier Clapham, of the National\nCity. expressed the opinion that \u201cthey\nwere after it and might get it, but he\ncould tell better in the afternoon.\u201d\n1f the sale is made it will be to\nfinancial interests identified with the\nNational Metropolitan, the Washington\nExchange and the Union Savings Bank,\nand in the interest of the latter insti\ntution,\nThe Nationa! City Bank was started\nthree vears ago, and has been very suc\ncessful, paving 10 per cent dividends\nand piling up a handsome surp\u2019us as\nwell.\nOfficial announcement of the sale Is\nexpected in a dav or two.\nFLYING MACHINE\nAGAIN SUCCESSFUL\nNORFOLK, May 11.\u2014Wilbur and Or\nville Wright, the Dayton, aeronauts,\nwi:o have been experimenting with their\naeroplane at Kill Devil Hill for nearly\ntwo years, and who have, during the\npasi week, made several successful\nflig'iis with their heavier than air fiy\ning machine, today made another sat\nisfactory ascension.\nThe machine rose from the ground\nwithout accident, soared like a bird to\na Leight of seventy-five feet, and sailed\ndown the coast for two and 2 half\nmiles. The daring inventors remained\nin the air for several hours.\nFinancial.\nW.B. Hibbs Co.\nflibbs Building\ner\nNew York Stock Exchange.\nMembers Washington Stock Exchanges\nChiicage Board of Trade,\n10CAY, BECURITIES\nbought and sod on sama\nfavorable terms as ws offer\nfor trading in New York\nstocks and bon\nThe Safest Investments\nAre those that do not fluctuats during dis\nturbed conditions of the money or stock\nmarkets, First deed of trust notes (first\nm s), well secured on real estates in\nthe District of Columbia, constitute \u201c\u2018giit\ngige\u2019\u2019 investments. They do not depend upon\nthe financial responsibility of individuals or\ncorporations for their stability, and are ex\nempt from taxation as personal property.\nWe can supply such investments in amounts\nfrom $500 upward. Send for booklet, \u201cCog\ncerning loans and Investments.\u201d\nSwartzell Rheem\nHensey Co.,\n727 15th St. N. W.\nUnder U. 8. Treasury Supervision\nHome Savings Bank,\nDon\u2019t Wait\nUntil you bave a geodly sum\nto start a savings account with.\nStart right away with what you\nhave, and add what you can\nto it each week. The 3% iu\nterest we pay will help i to\ngrow,\n7th and Mass. Ave. N. W.\nBRANCHES: 1\n7thand HSts. N. EB 436 7th St. S. WW,\na\nInvestigate Fully\nBefore Banking\nYour Money\nExperience teaches that care and\ntime spent in investigating the\nstrength and character of your bank\nis well worth while.\nWe invite your deposit account,\nbut we invite vou first to send for\nour financial statement, make every\ninguiry to satisfy yourself that this\nis \u201crhe stronge:\u00a2 financial institu\ntion south of Philadelphia and east\nof St. Louis.\u201d\nAMERICAN SECURITY\nAN D TRUST COMPANY\nNorthwest co